Weaksauce (adj.)

def. To use a computer glitch to score or win in a video sports game.

Originally, defined in Boulder CO circa 1994 while playing EA NHL '94.

If a player skated in front of the goal horizontally and shot, a glitch would cause the goally to "flop" and leave the goal area wide open. Purposefully shooting, such a shot would be considered "weaksauce".

Sessa: "Yzerman skates in front, shot, SCORE!!!"

ALL: "Whatever Sessa that was total WEAKSAUCE!!"

alt def. In relation to the sport of tennis; a serve or groundstroke with considerably less force than normal.  This term came in the mainstream after Andy Roddick used it during a first round match against Alexander Popov in the summer of 2004 at Wimbledon.  Popov kept hitting lobs which prompted the exclamation from Roddick "WEAKSAUCE!" in the second set as the ball was in the air for an extended period of time due to Popov's lob.  The term then spread throughout college and high school tennis teams and the general sports public to mean anything 'lame.'